As we can see from the plots below, weather seems to have some sort of impact on the departure delays of the flights from NYC. Although it is not possible for us to confirm whether it is these variables that are causing the delays, through the various plots below we have shown that there is a certain correlation between variables in the weather data set and the departure delay.

For temperature, we can see that there is a slight increase in the values of the departure delay for low temperatures and a relatively high delay at higher temperatures whereas at mild temperatures the delay is low.

Another variable that catches our attention is the presence of dew. As the amount of dew increases we can see that there is an increase in the departure delay which signifies some sort of correlation between the two variables. Similarly, we can see that with an increase in humidity the departure delay seems to increase as well.

Precipitation on the other hand seems to have a zero slope which shows that as precipitation increases there is no effect on the departure delay of the flights.

For windspeed and windgust we have a strange relation. This is something that we can dig deeper into to find out the cause for such a relation. It seems as if at low wind speed and low wind gust the delay is higher.Note here that the speed and gust are in mph.

We also need to keep in mind that these are just correlations between the departure delay and the various weather variables. We are NOT saying that these variables solely are causing the delay. There could be several other confounding variables that have a bigger hand in the delay.

Our findings above could be the reason why delays are occuring or they could be the reason for some other variable which in turn is causing the delay.

#Using the multiple plot function from cookbook-r.com
# Multiple plot function
#
# ggplot objects can be passed in ..., or to plotlist (as a list of ggplot objects)
# - cols:   Number of columns in layout
# - layout: A matrix specifying the layout. If present, 'cols' is ignored.
#
# If the layout is something like matrix(c(1,2,3,3), nrow=2, byrow=TRUE),
# then plot 1 will go in the upper left, 2 will go in the upper right, and
# 3 will go all the way across the bottom.
#
multiplot <- function(..., plotlist=NULL, file, cols=1, layout=NULL) {
  library(grid)

  # Make a list from the ... arguments and plotlist
  plots <- c(list(...), plotlist)

  numPlots = length(plots)

  # If layout is NULL, then use 'cols' to determine layout
  if (is.null(layout)) {
    # Make the panel
    # ncol: Number of columns of plots
    # nrow: Number of rows needed, calculated from # of cols
    layout <- matrix(seq(1, cols * ceiling(numPlots/cols)),
                    ncol = cols, nrow = ceiling(numPlots/cols))
  }

 if (numPlots==1) {
    print(plots[[1]])

  } else {
    # Set up the page
    grid.newpage()
    pushViewport(viewport(layout = grid.layout(nrow(layout), ncol(layout))))

    # Make each plot, in the correct location
    for (i in 1:numPlots) {
      # Get the i,j matrix positions of the regions that contain this subplot
      matchidx <- as.data.frame(which(layout == i, arr.ind = TRUE))

      print(plots[[i]], vp = viewport(layout.pos.row = matchidx$row,
                                      layout.pos.col = matchidx$col))
    }
  }
}

#Create all the ggplots on a single page
multiplot(p1,p2,p3,p4,p5,p6,p7,p8,p9,cols=3)

We started our exploratory analysis by first calculating the age of the flights which could be found by subtracting the year when they took flight last, that is, 2013 and the year in which they were manufactured. However, from the plot that we created we could see that there is an inverse correlation between the age of the flight and the departure delay. This means that as the flights get older and older and get used more, the delay reduces. This analysis did not look convincing and hence we performed another analysis that would make more sense.

As the number of seats increases on a flight we assume that the size of the flight increases. Our second analysis was to see if there was a delay in departure for heavier and bigger sized flights(more seats) than the smaller flights(lesser seats). To make the analysis clearer we segregated the plots on basis of manufacturers.

As can be seen from the plot, there isnt a lot of variance in delay for flights with lesser number of seats, however, for larger flights we can see a significant rise in delays as the seats increase. To further help our analysis and give it more clarity we have created a color encoding on basis of the engine which can help us recognize the different engines in the plot, especially for the manufacturers which have a lot of flights.

#Perform a left join between the data frames flights_NYC and planes_data 
#on their "tailnum"
flights_planes_data <- left_join(flights_NYC,planes_data,by="tailnum")

#Calculate the age of the planes by subtracting the year that it flew, 
#that is, 2013(year.x)
#and the year that it was manufactured in, that is, year.y
flights_planes_data$age <- flights_planes_data$year.x-flights_planes_data$year.y

#Create a plot to show seats vs departure delay and the engine is used as 
#a factor to differentiate via color
ggplot(flights_planes_data,aes(dep_delay,seats,col=as.factor(engine)))+
  geom_point(pch=19,cex=1.5)+
  xlab("Departure Delay")+
  ylab("Seats in a Flight")+
  facet_wrap(~manufacturer)+
  theme_bw()
